There's no database, just `state.todos` in memory + `localStorage`. The closest analog: `updateTodo` (app.js:64-66) does a full `.map()` over every todo to update one by `id`, and `toggleTodo`/`deleteTodo` similarly scan the whole array. At today's scale (a personal to-do list) this is irrelevant, but if the list ever grows large, lookups become O(n) per action instead of O(1):

```js
// Current: O(n) scan + O(n) array rebuild for a single update
function updateTodo(id, changes) {
  state.todos = state.todos.map((todo) => (todo.id === id ? { ...todo, ...changes } : todo));
}
```

Not worth fixing for this app's actual size — flagging only because it's the literal answer to "N+1-style" scans.

This is the real, actionable finding. `render()` (app.js:110-137) does `refs.todoList.innerHTML = ""` then rebuilds **every** todo item from scratch — on every single toggle, add, delete, or filter change. Consequences:

- Every event listener on every item is destroyed and recreated each time (app.js:149,156-159,168).
- The entrance animation (`requestAnimationFrame(() => item.classList.add("visible"))`, app.js:171) replays for **all** items, not just the one that changed — toggling one checkbox visibly re-animates the entire list.
- Editing input focus/selection is lost if something else triggers `sync()` mid-edit.

**Fix — event delegation + targeted DOM patch instead of full rebuild:**

```js
// Attach once, not per-item
refs.todoList.addEventListener("click", (event) => {
  const item = event.target.closest(".todo-item");
  if (!item) return;
  const id = item.dataset.id;
  if (event.target.closest(".check-btn")) toggleTodo(id);
  if (event.target.closest(".del-btn")) deleteTodo(id);
});

// createTodoItem no longer calls addEventListener per button,
// just sets item.dataset.id = todo.id

// render() only animates items that are actually new:
function render() {
  // ...
  todos.forEach((todo) => {
    const existing = refs.todoList.querySelector(`[data-id="${todo.id}"]`);
    if (existing) {
      existing.querySelector(".todo-text").classList.toggle("done", todo.completed);
      existing.querySelector(".check-btn").innerHTML = todo.completed ? "✅" : "";
    } else {
      const el = createTodoItem(todo);
      refs.todoList.appendChild(el);
      requestAnimationFrame(() => el.classList.add("visible"));
    }
  });
}
```

This removes listener churn, stops re-animating untouched rows, and avoids destroying/recreating DOM nodes that didn't change.

`render()` (app.js:112-113) calls `getActiveCount()` and `getCompletedCount()`. But `getCompletedCount()` (app.js:52-54) itself calls `getActiveCount()` again — so the array gets filtered twice for what should be a single pass:

```js
// Before: two .filter() passes over state.todos
function getActiveCount() {
  return state.todos.filter((todo) => !todo.completed).length;
}
function getCompletedCount() {
  return state.todos.length - getActiveCount(); // re-filters
}

// After: one pass, reused
function getCounts() {
  const total = state.todos.length;
  const active = state.todos.reduce((n, t) => n + (t.completed ? 0 : 1), 0);
  return { active, completed: total - active, total };
}
```

Negligible at current list sizes, but it's a free fix and removes a redundant computation called on every render.

